## 3D-SPECIFIC RULES (ALL CRITICAL)

### 3D-R1 — PIXEL RATIO CAP
THREE.js renderer MUST cap device pixel ratio to avoid GPU overload on Retina screens:
```js
renderer.setPixelRatio(Math.min(window.devicePixelRatio, 2));
```

---

### 3D-R2 — 3-TIER PROGRESSIVE FALLBACK (CRITICAL)

Low-end mobile phones can have WebGL support but still choke on a 3D scene.
A single WebGL check is not enough. You MUST implement all 3 tiers:

---

#### TIER 1 — No WebGL at all → Full CSS static fallback
Runs before the renderer is even created. If WebGL is unavailable, never initialise THREE.js at all.

```js
// Check BEFORE creating renderer
const testCanvas = document.createElement('canvas');
const hasWebGL = testCanvas.getContext('webgl2') || testCanvas.getContext('webgl');

if (!hasWebGL) {
  // Hide the canvas container, show the CSS fallback layer
  document.getElementById('canvas-container').style.display = 'none';
  document.getElementById('css-fallback').style.display = 'block';
  // STOP — do not initialise THREE.js at all
} else {
  initThreeScene(); // only runs if WebGL exists
}
```

CSS fallback layer — put this in every page that has a 3D scene:
```html
<!-- 3D canvas sits here normally -->
<div id="canvas-container">
  <canvas id="three-canvas"></canvas>
</div>

<!-- CSS fallback — hidden by default, shown when WebGL fails -->
<div id="css-fallback" style="display:none">
  <!-- Use a high-quality static image + CSS animations to mimic depth -->
  <div class="fallback-scene">
    <img src="/assets/hero-static.webp" alt="Pagani Utopia, front three-quarter view">
    <div class="fallback-glow"></div>      <!-- CSS radial-gradient glow -->
    <div class="fallback-particles"></div> <!-- CSS keyframe dot animation -->
  </div>
</div>
```

CSS for the fallback (must feel designed, not broken):
```css
.fallback-scene {
  position: relative;
  width: 100%;
  height: 100vh;
  background: #0a0a0a;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;
  overflow: hidden;
}
.fallback-scene img {
  max-width: 90%;
  object-fit: contain;
  /* Subtle float animation to suggest interactivity */
  animation: fallback-float 6s ease-in-out infinite;
}
.fallback-glow {
  position: absolute;
  inset: 0;
  background: radial-gradient(ellipse at 50% 60%, rgba(180,140,80,0.15), transparent 70%);
  pointer-events: none;
}
@keyframes fallback-float {
  0%, 100% { transform: translateY(0px);   }
  50%       { transform: translateY(-12px); }
}
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  /* Kill heavy animations — these cause motion sickness */
  .fallback-scene img  { animation: none; }
  .fallback-particles  { animation: none; }

  /* Preserve light transitions — UX still feels responsive, just not distracting */
  .fallback-glow       { transition-duration: 0.1s; }
}
```

